# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lorawan-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] In digital communications, **chirp spread spectrum** (**CSS**) is a spread spectrum technique that uses wideband linear frequency modulated chirp pulses to encode information.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] A chirp is a sinusoidal signal whose frequency increases or decreases over time (often with a polynomial expression for the relationship between time and frequency).
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] As with other spread spectrum methods, chirp spread spectrum uses its entire allocated bandwidth to broadcast a signal, making it robust to channel noise.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Further, because the chirps utilize a broad band of the spectrum, chirp spread spectrum is also resistant to multi-path fading even when operating at very low power.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] However, it is unlike direct-sequence spread spectrum (DSSS) or frequency-hopping spread spectrum (FHSS) in that it does not add any pseudo-random elements to the signal to help distinguish it from noise on the channel, instead relying on the linear nature of the chirp pulse.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Additionally, chirp spread spectrum is resistant to the Doppler effect, which is typical in mobile radio applications.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Chirp spread spectrum was originally designed to compete with ultra-wideband for precision ranging and low-rate wireless networks in the 2.45 GHz band.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] However, since the release of IEEE 802.15.4a (also known as IEEE 802.15.4a-2007), it is no longer actively being considered by the IEEE for standardization in the area of precision ranging.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Chirp spread spectrum is ideal for applications requiring low power usage and needing relatively low data rates (1 Mbit/s or less).
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] In particular, IEEE 802.15.4a specifies CSS as a technique for use in low-rate wireless personal area networks (LR-WPAN).
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] However, whereas IEEE 802.15.4-2006 standard specifies that WPANs encompass an area of 10 m or less, IEEE 802.15.4a-2007, specifies CSS as a physical layer to be used when longer ranges and devices moving at high speeds are part of your network.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Nanotron's CSS implementation was actually seen to work at a range of 570 meters between devices.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Further, Nanotron's implementation can work at data rates of up to 2 Mbit/s - higher than specified in 802.15.4a.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Finally, the IEEE 802.15.4a PHY standard actually mixes CSS encoding techniques with differential phase-shift keying modulation (DPSK) to achieve better data rates.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Chirp spread spectrum may also be used in the future for military applications as it is very difficult to detect and intercept when operating at low power.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] Very similar frequency swept waveforms are used in frequency modulated continuous wave radars (FM-CW) to measure range (distance); an unmodulated continuous wave Doppler radar can only measure range-rate (relative velocity along the line of sight).
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] FM-CW radars are very widely used as radio altimeters in aircraft.
[src:lorawan-deep/chirp-spread-spectrum] One application of chirp spread spectrum is LoRa.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The **ISM radio bands** are portions of the radio spectrum reserved internationally for *industrial, scientific and medical* (ISM) purposes, excluding applications in telecommunications.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Examples of applications for the use of radio frequency (RF) energy in these bands include RF heating, microwave ovens, and medical diathermy machines.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The powerful emissions of these devices can create electromagnetic interference and disrupt radio communication using the same frequency, so these devices are limited to certain bands of frequencies.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In general, communications equipment operating in ISM bands must tolerate any interference generated by ISM applications, and users have no regulatory protection from ISM device operation in these bands.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Cordless phones, Bluetooth devices, near-field communication (NFC) devices, garage door openers, baby monitors, and wireless computer networks (Wi-Fi) may all use the ISM frequencies, although these low-power transmitters are not considered to be ISM devices.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands are defined by the ITU Radio Regulations (article 5) in footnotes 5.138, 5.150, and 5.280 of the Radio Regulations.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Individual countries' use of the bands designated in these sections may differ due to variations in national radio regulations.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Because communication devices using the ISM bands must tolerate any interference from ISM equipment, unlicensed operations are typically permitted to use these bands, since unlicensed operation typically needs to be tolerant of interference from other devices anyway.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands share allocations with unlicensed and licensed operations; however, due to the high likelihood of harmful interference, licensed use of the bands is typically low.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In the United States, uses of the ISM bands are governed by Part 18 of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) rules, while Part 15 contains the rules for unlicensed communication devices, even those that share ISM frequencies.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In Europe, the ETSI develops standards for the use of short-range devices, some of which operate in ISM bands.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The use of the ISM bands is regulated by the national spectrum regulation authorities that are members of the CEPT.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The allocation of radio frequencies is provided according to *Article 5* of the ITU Radio Regulations (edition 2012).
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In order to improve harmonisation in spectrum utilisation, the majority of service allocations stipulated in this document were incorporated in national tables of frequency allocations and utilisations which are within the responsibilities of the appropriate national administrations.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The allocation might be primary, secondary, exclusive, or shared.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Exclusive or shared utilization is within the responsibility of administrations.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] ITU RR, (Footnote 5.280) = In Germany, Austria, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, North Macedonia, Liechtenstein, Montenegro, Portugal, Serbia, Slovenia and Switzerland, the band 433.05–434.79 MHz (center frequency 433.92 MHz) is designated for *ISM applications*.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Radio communication services of these countries operating within this band must accept harmful interference which may be caused by these applications.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands were first established at the International Telecommunications Conference of the ITU in Atlantic City, 1947.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The American delegation specifically proposed several bands, including the now commonplace 2.4 GHz band, to accommodate the then nascent process of microwave heating; however, FCC annual reports of that time suggest that much preparation was done ahead of these presentations.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Radio frequencies in the ISM bands have been used for communication purposes, although such devices may experience interference from non-communication sources.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In the U.S., the FCC first made unlicensed spread spectrum available in the ISM bands in rules adopted on May 9, 1985.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The FCC action was proposed by Michael Marcus of the FCC staff in 1980 and the subsequent regulatory action took five more years.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] It was part of a broader proposal to allow civil use of spread spectrum technology and was opposed at the time by mainstream equipment manufacturers and many radio system operators.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Many other countries later developed similar regulations, enabling use of this technology.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The original ISM specifications envisioned that the bands would be used primarily for noncommunication purposes, such as heating.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The bands are still widely used for these purposes.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] For many people, the most commonly encountered ISM device is the home microwave oven operating at 2.45 GHz which uses microwaves to cook food.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Industrial heating is another big application area; such as induction heating, microwave heat treating, plastic softening, and plastic welding processes.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In medical settings, shortwave and microwave diathermy machines use radio waves in the ISM bands to apply deep heating to the body for relaxation and healing.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] More recently hyperthermia therapy uses microwaves to heat tissue to kill cancer cells.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] These are sometimes called "non ISM" uses since they do not fall under the originally envisioned "industrial", "scientific", and "medical" application areas.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] One of the largest applications has been wireless networking (Wi-Fi).
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The IEEE 802.11ah wireless networking protocols, the standards on which almost all wireless systems are based, use the ISM bands.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Virtually all laptops, tablet computers, computer printers and cellphones now have 802.11 wireless modems using the 2.4 and 5.7 GHz ISM bands.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Bluetooth is another networking technology using the 2.4 GHz band, which can be problematic given the probability of interference.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Near-field communication (NFC) devices such as proximity cards and contactless smart cards use the lower-frequency 13 and 27 MHz ISM bands.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Multiple international LoRa standards use ISM bands for low-power, long-range, low-rate data transmission.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Some electrodeless lamp designs are ISM devices, which use RF emissions to excite fluorescent tubes.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Sulfur lamps are commercially available plasma lamps, which use 2.45 GHz magnetrons to heat sulfur into a brightly glowing plasma.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Long-distance wireless power systems have been proposed and experimented with which would use high-power transmitters and rectennas, in lieu of overhead transmission lines and underground cables, to send power to remote locations.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] NASA has studied using microwave power transmission on 2.45 GHz to send energy collected by solar power satellites back to the ground.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Also in space applications, a helicon double-layer ion thruster is a prototype spacecraft propulsion engine which uses a 13.56 MHz transmission to break down and heat gas into plasma.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In recent years ISM bands have also been shared with (non-ISM) license-free error-tolerant communications applications such as wireless sensor networks in the 915 MHz and 2.450 GHz bands, as well as wireless LANs and cordless phones in the 915 MHz, 2.450 GHz, and 5.800 GHz bands.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Because unlicensed devices are required to be tolerant of ISM emissions in these bands, unlicensed low-power users are generally able to operate in these bands without causing problems for ISM users.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] ISM equipment does not necessarily include a radio receiver in the ISM band (e.g. a microwave oven does not have a receiver).
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In the United States, according to 47 CFR Part 15.5, low power communication devices must accept interference from licensed users of that frequency band, and the Part 15 device must not cause interference to licensed users.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Note that the 915 MHz band should not be used in countries outside Region 2, except those that specifically allow it, such as Australia (915 MHz to 928 MHz) and Israel, especially those that use the GSM-900 band for cellphones.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands are also widely used for radio-frequency identification (RFID) applications with the most commonly used band being the 13.56 MHz band used by systems compliant with ISO/IEC 14443 including those used by biometric passports and contactless smart cards.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In Europe, the use of the ISM band is covered by Short Range Device regulations issued by European Commission, based on technical recommendations by CEPT and standards by ETSI.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] In most of Europe, LPD433 band is allowed for license-free voice communication in addition to PMR446.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Wireless LANs and cordless phones can also use bands other than those shared with ISM, but such uses require approval on a country by country basis.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] DECT phones use allocated spectrum outside the ISM bands that differs in Europe and North America.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Ultra-wideband LANs require more spectrum than the ISM bands can provide, so the relevant standards such as IEEE 802.15.4a are designed to make use of spectrum outside the ISM bands.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Despite the fact that these additional bands are outside the official ITU-R ISM bands, because they are used for the same types of low power personal communications, they are sometimes incorrectly referred to as ISM bands as well.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Several brands of radio control equipment use the 2.4 GHz band range for low power remote control of toys, from gas powered cars to miniature aircraft.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Worldwide Digital Cordless Telecommunications or WDCT is a technology that uses the 2.4 GHz radio spectrum.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Google's Project Loon used ISM bands (specifically 2.4 and 5.8 GHz bands) for balloon-to-balloon and balloon-to-ground communications.
[src:lorawan-deep/ism-radio-band] Pursuant to 47 CFR Part 97 some ISM bands are used by licensed amateur radio operators for communication – including amateur television.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] The technology is primarily used for applications where small amounts of data need to be transmitted infrequently from hard-to-reach locations.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] The technology covers the physical layer, while other technologies and protocols such as LoRaWAN cover the upper layers.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] It can achieve data rates between 0.3 kbit/s and 27 kbit/s, depending upon the spreading factor.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] LoRa uses a proprietary spread spectrum modulation that is similar to and a derivative of chirp spread spectrum (CSS) modulation.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] Each symbol is represented by a cyclic shifted chirp over the bandwidth centered around the base frequency.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] The spreading factor (SF) is a selectable radio parameter from 5 to 12 and represents the number of bits sent per symbol and in addition determines how much the information is spread over time.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] There are $M=2^{\mathrm {SF} }$ different initial frequencies of the cyclic shifted chirp across the bandwidth around the center frequency.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] The symbol rate is determined by $R_{s}=B/M$ .
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] LoRa can tradeoff data rate for sensitivity (assuming a fixed channel bandwidth B ) by selecting the SF, i.e. the amount of spread used.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] A lower SF corresponds to a higher data rate but a worse sensitivity, a higher SF implies a better sensitivity but a lower data rate.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] Compared to lower SF, sending the same amount of data with higher SF needs more transmission time, known as time-on-air.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] More time-on-air means that the modem is transmitting for a longer time and consuming more energy.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] Typical LoRa modems support transmit powers up to +22 dBm.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] However, the regulations of the respective country may additionally limit the allowed transmit power.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] Higher transmit power results in higher signal power at the receiver and hence a higher link budget, but at the cost of consuming more energy.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] There are measurement studies of LoRa performance with regard to energy consumption, communication distances, and medium access efficiency.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] According to the LoRa Development Portal, the range provided by LoRa can be up to 3 miles (4.8 km) in urban areas, and up to 10 miles (16 km) or more in rural areas (line of sight).
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] In addition, LoRa uses forward error correction coding to improve resilience against interference.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] LoRa's high range is characterized by high wireless link budgets of around 155 dB to 170 dB.
[src:lorawan-deep/lora] Range extenders for LoRa are called LoRaX.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] Together, LoRa and LoRaWAN provide a solution for connecting low-power devices over long distances, making them a key technology for the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] The technology is primarily used for applications where small amounts of data need to be transmitted infrequently from hard-to-reach locations, such as in smart agriculture, industrial monitoring, and asset tracking.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] The technology was originally developed by the French company Cycleo, which was acquired by Semtech in 2012, and the LoRaWAN standard is now managed by the LoRa Alliance.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] LoRaWAN devices have geolocation capabilities used for trilaterating positions of devices via timestamps from gateways.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] LoRa's geolocation feature, combined with the technology's long-range and low-power characteristics, makes it suitable for a wide range of Internet of Things (IoT) applications where assets are dispersed and battery life is critical.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] LoRaWAN is widely used for asset tracking, particularly for non-powered assets that require a tracking system with a long battery life.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] Because it does not rely on cellular networks, it is an effective technology for monitoring moving objects in areas with poor or no GSM signal, such as in remote areas or inside large metal shipping containers.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] A common application is in the track and trace of construction and railway equipment.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] For example, LoRaWAN trackers are used in Switzerland to monitor the location of construction wagons, providing security against theft and improving the efficiency of fleet logistics.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] In precision agriculture, LoRaWAN sensors are used to create managing information systems that optimize farming operations.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] Low-power sensors are deployed across large fields to monitor soil moisture, temperature, and nutrient levels, allowing for more efficient irrigation and fertilization.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] The technology is also used for tracking the location and health of livestock.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] LoRaWAN is used for smart city applications.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] While LoRa defines the lower physical layer, LoRaWAN is the system architecture for the network.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] LoRaWAN defines the communication protocol for managing communication between low-power end-node devices and gateways.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] Devices in the network are asynchronous and transmit when they have data available to send.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] Data transmitted by an end-node device is received by multiple gateways, which then forward the data packets to the centralized network server.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] The data is then forwarded to an associated application server.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] In the wireless communication, particularly across the IoT applications, collision avoidance is essential for reliable communication and overall spectral efficiency.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] Previously, LoRaWAN has relied upon ALOHA as the medium access control (MAC) layer protocol, but to improve this, the LoRa Alliance's Technical Recommendation TR013 introduced CSMA-CA.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] Employing the CAD based CSMA technique specified in TR013 enhances LoRaWAN's spectrum efficiency and ensures more reliable device communication, including in congested environments.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] TR013 is based on the LMAC and is the first industry-academia collaboration of LoRa Alliance to have resulted in a Technical Recommendation.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] The **LoRa Alliance** is nonprofit organization located in Fremont, California supporting the LoRaWAN standard and deployments in remote or hard-to-reach locations.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] Members include Actility, Amazon Web Services, Cisco, Everynet, Helium, Kerlink, MachineQ, Microsoft, MikroTik, Minol Zenner, Netze BW, Semtech, Senet, STMicroelectronics, TEKTELIC,Orbiwise SA and The Things Industries.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] In 2018, the LoRa Alliance had over 100 LoRaWAN network operators in over 100 countries; in 2023, there are nearly 200, providing coverage in nearly every country in the world.
[src:lorawan-deep/lorawan] On October 1, 2024, Cisco announced it is "exiting the LoRaWAN space" with no planned migration for Cisco LoRaWAN gateways.
[src:lorawan-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] A **low-power, wide-area network** (**LPWAN** or **LPWA network**) is a type of wireless telecommunication wide area network designed to allow long-range communication at a low bit rate between IoT devices, such as sensors operated on a battery.
[src:lorawan-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] Low power, low bit rate, and intended use distinguish this type of network from a wireless WAN that is designed to connect users or businesses, and carry more data, using more power.
[src:lorawan-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] The LPWAN data rate ranges from 0.3 kbit/s to 50 kbit/s per channel.
[src:lorawan-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] A LPWAN may be used to create a private wireless sensor network, but may also be a service or infrastructure offered by a third party, allowing the owners of sensors to deploy them in the field without investing in gateway technology.
[src:lorawan-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] **Power:** LPWAN manufacturers claim years to decades of usable life from built-in batteries, but real-world application tests have not confirmed this.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] These are similar to wireless ad hoc networks in the sense that they rely on wireless connectivity and spontaneous formation of networks so that sensor data can be transported wirelessly.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs monitor physical conditions, such as temperature, sound, and pressure.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Modern networks are bi-directional, both collecting data and enabling control of sensor activity.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The development of these networks was motivated by military applications such as battlefield surveillance.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Such networks are used in industrial and consumer applications, such as industrial process monitoring and control and machine health monitoring and agriculture.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A WSN is built of "nodes" – from a few to hundreds or thousands, where each node is connected to other sensors.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Each such node typically has several parts: a radio transceiver with an internal antenna or connection to an external antenna, a microcontroller, an electronic circuit for interfacing with the sensors and an energy source, usually a battery or an embedded form of energy harvesting.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A sensor node might vary in size from a shoebox to (theoretically) a grain of dust, although microscopic dimensions have yet to be realized.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor node cost is similarly variable, ranging from a few to hundreds of dollars, depending on node sophistication.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Size and cost constraints constrain resources such as energy, memory, computational speed and communications bandwidth.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The topology of a WSN can vary from a simple star network to an advanced multi-hop wireless mesh network.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Propagation can employ routing or flooding.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] As of 2010, wireless sensor networks had deployed approximately 120 million remote units worldwide.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Area monitoring is a common application of WSNs.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] In area monitoring, the WSN is deployed over a region where some phenomenon is to be monitored.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A military example is the use of sensors to detect enemy intrusion; a civilian example is the geo-fencing of gas or oil pipelines.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There are several types of sensor networks for medical applications: implanted, wearable, and environment-embedded.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Implantable medical devices are those that are inserted inside the human body.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wearable devices are used on the body surface of a human or just at close proximity of the user.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Environment-embedded systems employ sensors contained in the environment.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Possible applications include body position measurement, location of persons, overall monitoring of ill patients in hospitals and at home.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Devices embedded in the environment track the physical state of a person for continuous health diagnosis, using as input the data from a network of depth cameras, a sensing floor, or other similar devices.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Body-area networks can collect information about an individual's health, fitness, and energy expenditure.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] In health care applications the privacy and authenticity of user data has prime importance.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Especially due to the integration of sensor networks, with IoT, the user authentication becomes more challenging; however, a solution is presented in recent work.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been used to monitor various species and habitats, beginning with the Great Duck Island Deployment, including marmots, cane toads in Australia and zebras in Kenya.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There are many applications in monitoring environmental parameters, examples of which are given below.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] They share the extra challenges of harsh environments and reduced power supply.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Experiments have shown that personal exposure to air pollution in cities can vary a lot.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, it is of interest to have higher temporal and spatial resolution of pollutants and particulates.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] For research purposes, wireless sensor networks have been deployed to monitor the concentration of dangerous gases for citizens (e.g., in London).
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] However, sensors for gases and particulate matter suffer from high unit-to-unit variability, cross-sensitivities, and (concept) drift.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Moreover, the quality of data is currently insufficient for trustworthy decision-making, as field calibration leads to unreliable measurement results, and frequent recalibration might be required.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A possible solution could be blind calibration or the usage of mobile references.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A network of Sensor Nodes can be installed in a forest to detect when a fire has started.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The nodes can be equipped with sensors to measure temperature, humidity and gases which are produced by fire in the trees or vegetation.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The early detection is crucial for a successful action of the firefighters; thanks to Wireless Sensor Networks, the fire brigade will be able to know when a fire is started and how it is spreading.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A landslide detection system makes use of a wireless sensor network to detect the slight movements of soil and changes in various parameters that may occur before or during a landslide.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Through the data gathered it may be possible to know the impending occurrence of landslides long before it actually happens.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Water quality monitoring involves analyzing water properties in dams, rivers, lakes and oceans, as well as underground water reserves.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The use of many wireless distributed sensors enables the creation of a more accurate map of the water status, and allows the permanent deployment of monitoring stations in locations of difficult access, without the need of manual data retrieval.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks can be effective in preventing adverse consequences of natural disasters, like floods.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless nodes have been deployed successfully in rivers, where changes in water levels must be monitored in real time.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been developed for machinery condition-based maintenance (CBM) as they offer significant cost savings and enable new functionality.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensors can be placed in locations difficult or impossible to reach with a wired system, such as rotating machinery and untethered vehicles.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks also are used for the collection of data for monitoring of environmental information.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This can be as simple as monitoring the temperature in a fridge or the level of water in overflow tanks in nuclear power plants.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The statistical information can then be used to show how systems have been working.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The advantage of WSNs over conventional loggers is the "live" data feed that is possible.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Monitoring the quality and level of water includes many activities such as checking the quality of underground or surface water and ensuring a country's water infrastructure for the benefit of both human and animal.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] It may be used to protect the wastage of water.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WSN can be used to monitor the condition of civil infrastructure and related geo-physical processes close to real time, and over long periods through data logging, using appropriately interfaced sensors.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are used to monitor wine production, both in the field and the cellar.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The Wide Area Tracking System (WATS) is a prototype network for detecting a ground-based nuclear device such as a nuclear "briefcase bomb".
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WATS is being developed at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL).
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would be made up of wireless gamma and neutron sensors connected through a communications network.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Data picked up by the sensors undergoes "data fusion", which converts the information into easily interpreted forms; this data fusion is the most important aspect of the system.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The data fusion process occurs *within* the sensor network rather than at a centralized computer and is performed by a specially developed algorithm based on Bayesian statistics.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would not use a centralized computer for analysis because researchers found that factors such as latency and available bandwidth tended to create significant bottlenecks.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Data processed in the field by the network itself (by transferring small amounts of data between neighboring sensors) is faster and makes the network more scalable.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] An important factor in WATS development is *ease of deployment*, since more sensors both improves the detection rate and reduces false alarms.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WATS sensors could be deployed in permanent positions or mounted in vehicles for mobile protection of specific locations.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] One barrier to the implementation of WATS is the size, weight, energy requirements and cost of currently available wireless sensors.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The development of improved sensors is a major component of current research at the Nonproliferation, Arms Control, and International Security (NAI) Directorate at LLNL.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] House of Representatives' Military Research and Development Subcommittee on October 1, 1997, during a hearing on nuclear terrorism and countermeasures.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] On August 4, 1998, in a subsequent meeting of that subcommittee, Chairman Curt Weldon stated that research funding for WATS had been cut by the Clinton administration to a subsistence level and that the program had been poorly re-organized.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Studies show that using sensors for incident monitoring improve the response of firefighters and police to an unexpected situation.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] For an early detection of incidents we can use acoustic sensors to detect a spike in the noise of the city because of a possible accident, or use termic sensors to detect a possible fire.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Using low-power electronics, WSN:s can be cost-efficiently applied also in supply chains in various industries.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Cross-layer is becoming an important studying area for wireless communications.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The traditional layered approach does not have the ability to adapt to the environmental change.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Because of the interference between the different users, access conflicts, fading, and the change of environment in the wireless sensor networks, traditional layered approach for wired networks is not applicable to wireless networks.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] So the cross-layer can be used to make the optimal modulation to improve the transmission performance, such as data rate, energy efficiency, quality of service (QoS), etc.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor nodes can be imagined as small computers which are extremely basic in terms of their interfaces and their components.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] They usually consist of a *processing unit* with limited computational power and limited memory, *sensors* or MEMS (including specific conditioning circuitry), a *communication device* (usually radio transceivers or alternatively optical), and a power source usually in the form of a battery.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Other possible inclusions are energy harvesting modules, secondary ASICs, and possibly secondary communication interface (e.g.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The base stations are one or more components of the WSN with much more computational, energy and communication resources.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] They act as a gateway between sensor nodes and the end user as they typically forward data from the WSN on to a server.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Other special components in routing based networks are routers, designed to compute, calculate and distribute the routing tables.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] One major challenge in a WSN is to produce *low cost* and *tiny* sensor nodes.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There are an increasing number of small companies producing WSN hardware and the commercial situation can be compared to home computing in the 1970s.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Many of the nodes are still in the research and development stage, particularly their software.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Also inherent to sensor network adoption is the use of very low power methods for radio communication and data acquisition.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] In many applications, a WSN communicates with a local area network or wide area network through a gateway.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The Gateway acts as a bridge between the WSN and the other network.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This enables data to be stored and processed by devices with more resources, for example, in a remotely located server.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A wireless wide area network used primarily for low-power devices is known as a Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN).
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There are several wireless standards and solutions for sensor node connectivity.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Thread and Zigbee can connect sensors operating at 2.4 GHz with a data rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Many use a lower frequency to increase radio range (typically 1 km), for example Z-wave operates at 915 MHz (in North America) and in the EU 868 MHz has been widely used but these have a lower data rate (typically 50 kbit/s).
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The IEEE 802.15.4 working group provides a standard for low power device connectivity and commonly sensors and smart meters use one of these standards for connectivity.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] With the emergence of Internet of Things, many other proposals have been made to provide sensor connectivity.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] LoRa is a form of LPWAN which provides long range low power wireless connectivity for devices, which has been used in smart meters and other long range sensor applications.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] NarrowBand IOT and LTE-M can connect up to millions of sensors and devices using cellular technology.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Energy is the scarcest resource of WSN nodes, and it determines the lifetime of WSNs.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs may be deployed in large numbers in various environments, including remote and hostile regions, where ad hoc communications are a key component.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Lifetime maximization: Energy/Power Consumption of the sensing device should be minimized and sensor nodes should be energy efficient since their limited energy resource determines their lifetime.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] To conserve power, wireless sensor nodes normally power off both the radio transmitter and the radio receiver when not in use.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are composed of low-energy, small-size, and low-range unattended sensor nodes.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Recently, it has been observed that by periodically turning on and off the sensing and communication capabilities of sensor nodes, we can significantly reduce the active time and thus prolong network lifetime.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] However, this duty cycling may result in high network latency, routing overhead, and neighbor discovery delays due to asynchronous sleep and wake-up scheduling.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] These limitations call for a countermeasure for duty-cycled wireless sensor networks which should minimize routing information, routing traffic load, and energy consumption.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers from Sungkyunkwan University have proposed a lightweight non-increasing delivery-latency interval routing referred as LNDIR.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This scheme can discover minimum latency routes at each non-increasing delivery-latency interval instead of each time slot.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Simulation experiments demonstrated the validity of this novel approach in minimizing routing information stored at each sensor.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Furthermore, this novel routing can also guarantee the minimum delivery latency from each source to the sink.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Performance improvements of up to 12-fold and 11-fold are observed in terms of routing traffic load reduction and energy efficiency, respectively, as compared to existing schemes.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Operating systems for wireless sensor network nodes are typically less complex than general-purpose operating systems.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] They more strongly resemble embedded systems, for two reasons.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] First, wireless sensor networks are typically deployed with a particular application in mind, rather than as a general platform.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Second, a need for low costs and low power leads most wireless sensor nodes to have low-power microcontrollers ensuring that mechanisms such as virtual memory are either unnecessary or too expensive to implement.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] It is therefore possible to use embedded operating systems such as eCos or uC/OS for sensor networks.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] However, such operating systems are often designed with real-time properties.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS, developed by David Culler, is perhaps the first operating system specifically designed for wireless sensor networks.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS is based on an event-driven programming model instead of multithreading.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS programs are composed of *event handlers* and *tasks* with run-to-completion semantics.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] When an external event occurs, such as an incoming data packet or a sensor reading, TinyOS signals the appropriate event handler to handle the event.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Event handlers can post tasks that are scheduled by the TinyOS kernel some time later.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] LiteOS is a newly developed OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides UNIX-like abstraction and support for the C programming language.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Contiki, developed by Adam Dunkels, is an OS which uses a simpler programming style in C while providing advances such as 6LoWPAN and Protothreads.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] RIOT (operating system) is a more recent real-time OS including similar functionality to Contiki.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] PreonVM is an OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides 6LoWPAN based on Contiki and support for the Java programming language.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Examples include Xively and the Wikisensing platform Archived 2021-06-09 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Such platforms simplify online collaboration between users over diverse data sets ranging from energy and environment data to that collected from transport services.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Other services include allowing developers to embed real-time graphs & widgets in websites; analyse and process historical data pulled from the data feeds; send real-time alerts from any datastream to control scripts, devices and environments.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] At present, agent-based modeling and simulation is the only paradigm which allows the simulation of complex behavior in the environments of wireless sensors (such as flocking).
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based simulation of wireless sensor and ad hoc networks is a relatively new paradigm.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based modelling was originally based on social simulation.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Network simulators like Opnet, Tetcos NetSim and NS can be used to simulate a wireless sensor network.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Network localization refers to the problem of estimating the location of wireless sensor nodes during deployments and in dynamic settings.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] For ultra-low power sensors, size, cost and environment precludes the use of Global Positioning System receivers on sensors.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] In 2000, Nirupama Bulusu, John Heidemann and Deborah Estrin first motivated and proposed a radio connectivity based system for localization of wireless sensor networks.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Subsequently, such localization systems have been referred to as range free localization systems, and many localization systems for wireless sensor networks have been subsequently proposed including AHLoS, APS, and Stardust.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Sensors and devices used in wireless sensor networks are state-of-the-art technology with the lowest possible price.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The sensor measurements we get from these devices are therefore often noisy, incomplete and inaccurate.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers studying wireless sensor networks hypothesize that much more information can be extracted from hundreds of unreliable measurements spread across a field of interest than from a smaller number of high-quality, high-reliability instruments with the same total cost.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Macro-programming is a term coined by Matt Welsh.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] It refers to programming the entire sensor network as an ensemble, rather than individual sensor nodes.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Another way to macro-program a network is to view the sensor network as a database, which was popularized by the TinyDB system developed by Sam Madden.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Reprogramming is the process of updating the code on the sensor nodes.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The most feasible form of reprogramming is remote reprogramming whereby the code is disseminated wirelessly while the nodes are deployed.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Different reprogramming protocols exist that provide different levels of speed of operation, reliability, energy expenditure, requirement of code resident on the nodes, suitability to different wireless environments, resistance to DoS, etc.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Infrastructure-less architecture (i.e. no gateways are included, etc.) and inherent requirements (i.e. unattended working environment, etc.) of WSNs might pose several weak points that attract adversaries.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, security is a big concern when WSNs are deployed for special applications such as military and healthcare.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Owing to their unique characteristics, traditional security methods of computer networks would be useless (or less effective) for WSNs.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Hence, lack of security mechanisms would cause intrusions towards those networks.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] These intrusions need to be detected and mitigation methods should be applied.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There have been important innovations in securing wireless sensor networks.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Most wireless embedded networks use omni-directional antennas and therefore neighbors can overhear communication in and out of nodes.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This was used this to develop a primitive called "*local monitoring*" which was used for detection of sophisticated attacks, like blackhole or wormhole, which degrade the throughput of large networks to close-to-zero.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This primitive has since been used by many researchers and commercial wireless packet sniffers.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This was subsequently refined for more sophisticated attacks such as with collusion, mobility, and multi-antenna, multi-channel devices.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] If a centralized architecture is used in a sensor network and the central node fails, then the entire network will collapse, however the reliability of the sensor network can be increased by using a distributed control architecture.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] To provide nodes with backup in case of failure of the central node.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There is also no centralised body to allocate the resources and they have to be self organized.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The data gathered from wireless sensor networks is usually saved in the form of numerical data in a central base station.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] To reduce communication costs some algorithms remove or reduce nodes' redundant sensor information and avoid forwarding data that is of no use.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This technique has been used, for instance, for distributed anomaly detection or distributed optimization.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] As nodes can inspect the data they forward, they can measure averages or directionality for example of readings from other nodes.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] For example, in sensing and monitoring applications, it is generally the case that neighboring sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation reduces the amount of network traffic which helps to reduce energy consumption on sensor nodes.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This is a form of in-network processing where sensor nodes are assumed to be unsecured with limited available energy, while the base station is assumed to be secure with unlimited available energy.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation complicates the already existing security challenges for wireless sensor networks and requires new security techniques tailored specifically for these scenarios.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Providing security to aggregate data in wireless sensor networks is known as *secure data aggregation in WSN*. were the first few works discussing techniques for secure data aggregation in wireless sensor networks.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Two main security challenges in secure data aggregation are confidentiality and integrity of data.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] While encryption is traditionally used to provide end to end confidentiality in wireless sensor network, the aggregators in a secure data aggregation scenario need to decrypt the encrypted data to perform aggregation.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This exposes the plaintext at the aggregators, making the data vulnerable to attacks from an adversary.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Similarly an aggregator can inject false data into the aggregate and make the base station accept false data.
[src:lorawan-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Thus, while data aggregation improves energy efficiency of a network, it complicates the existing security challenges.
